                        <msContents>

                            <summary>an explanation of and short text in the Kabardian alphabet by
                                Shora Gha Beg Mirza (?= <persName key="person_13798002">Nogmov, Sh.
                                    B. (Shora Bekmurzovich), approximately
                                1801-1844</persName></summary>
                            <textLang mainLang="kbd">Kabardian (East Circassian/Adyghe) in an
                                experiemental Arabic-based script</textLang>

                            <msItem xml:id="MS_Ouseley_159-item1" n="2">
                                <locus from="43a" to="52a">folios 43a-52a</locus>
                                <author key="person_13798002" cert="medium">
                                    <persName xml:lang="rus-Latn-x-lc">Nogmov, Sh. B. (Shora
                                        Bekmurzovich), approximately 1801-1844</persName><lb/>
                                    <persName xml:lang="kbd-Latn-x-lc">Năgmă Băchmyrză i k"uă
                                        Shoră</persName><lb/>
                                    <persName xml:lang="kbd">Нэгумэ Бэчмырзэ и къуэ Шорэ</persName><lb/>
                                    <persName xml:lang="kbd">نہگومہ بہچمہرہہ ی قوہ شۆرہ</persName><lb/>
                                    <persName xml:lang="rus-Latn-x-lc">Shora Bekmurovich
                                        Nogmov</persName><lb/>
                                    <persName xml:lang="rus">Шора Бекмурзович Ногмов</persName>
                                </author>
                                <title key="work_23489" xml:lang="eng" type="desc">Adighebja Alif-Beija or The
                                    Circassian Alphabet By Shora Gha Beg Mirza A Kabardian
                                    Chief</title>
                                <title key="work_23489" xml:lang="kbd">اىدىگہ‍ىبذہ اىلىف بېیڞېی</title>
                                <title key="work_23489" xml:lang="kbd">Адыгэбзэ алифбейшей [sic?]</title>
                                <title key="work_23489" xml:lang="kbd-Latn-x-lc">Adygăbză alifbeĭsheĭ
                                    [sic?]</title>
                                <incipit>ا ب د ج ح خ</incipit>
                                <listBibl>
                                    <bibl>Урыс, Хь. Щ. Адыгэбзэм и тхыдэ: ӏыхьитӏу зэхэлъу. Налшык:
                                        Эльбурс, 2000.</bibl>
                                </listBibl>
                                <textLang mainLang="kbd">Kabardian (Circassian) in Arabic script
                                    with some Cyrillic and Latin script equivalents in the
                                    back</textLang>
                                <note>The title is given as <title xml:lang="eng" type="desc">Adighebja Alif-Beija or The
                                    Circassian Alphabet</title> on <locus from="43a"
                                        to="43a">folio 43a</locus> and <title key="" xml:lang="kbd">اىدىگہ‍ىبذہ اىلىف بېیڞېی</title> in the colophon on <locus from="52a"
                                            to="52a">folio 52a</locus>. The second word of the title (Alifbeija / اىلىف بېیڞېی) does not
                                    correspond to any known word in Kabardian for the Arabic script
                                    (alifba). The author (and perhaps also scribe) is given as
                                    "Shora Gha Beg Mirza A Kabardian Chief" on <locus from="43a"
                                        to="43a">folio 43a</locus> in a later hand. The name is
                                    difficult to trace in that form, but this alphabet looks very
                                    similar (if not identical) to that proposed by <persName
                                        xml:lang="rus-Latn-x-lc" key="person_13798002">Shora
                                        Bekmurzovich Nogmov (roughly 1801-1844)</persName>, so the
                                    "Gha" element is likely an error, perhaps some mutation of the
                                    title "Agha" or a misinterpretation of the patronymic formula
                                    element "и къуэ".</note>
                            </msItem>

                        </msContents>

